{"title_page": "Homeland (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Short description|American political thriller television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Homeland\n| image = HomelandTVSeries.jpg\n| caption = \n| genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Serial (radio and television)|Serial drama]]\n* [[Spy fiction|Espionage thriller]]\n* [[Psychological thriller]]\n* [[Political thriller]]\n}}\n| based_on = {{based_on|''[[Prisoners of War (TV series)|Prisoners of War]]''|[[Gideon Raff]]}}\n| developer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Howard Gordon]]\n* [[Alex Gansa]]\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Claire Danes]]\n* [[Damian Lewis]]\n* [[Morena Baccarin]]\n* [[David Harewood]]\n* [[Diego Klattenhoff]]\n* [[Jackson Pace]]\n* [[Morgan Saylor]]\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]]\n* [[Jamey Sheridan]]\n* [[David Marciano]]\n* [[Navid Negahban]]\n* [[Rupert Friend]]\n* [[Sarita Choudhury]]\n* [[Tracy Letts]]\n* [[F. Murray Abraham]]\n* [[Nazanin Boniadi]]\n* [[Laila Robins]]\n* [[Sebastian Koch]]\n* [[Miranda Otto]]\n* [[Alexander Fehling]]\n* [[Sarah Sokolovic]]\n* [[Elizabeth Marvel]]\n* [[Maury Sterling]]\n* [[Linus Roache]]\n* [[Jake Weber]]\n* [[Morgan Spector]]\n* [[Costa Ronin]]\n* [[Nimrat Kaur]]\n* [[Numan Acar]]\n}}\n| composer = [[Sean Callery]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 8\n| num_episodes = 92\n| list_episodes = List of Homeland episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Alex Gansa\n* Howard Gordon\n* Gideon Raff\n* [[Michael Cuesta]]\n* Avi Nir\n* Ran Telem\n* [[Henry Bromell]]\n* [[Alexander Cary, Master of Falkland|Alexander Cary]]\n* [[Chip Johannessen]]\n* [[Meredith Stiehm]]\n* [[Lesli Linka Glatter]]\n* Patrick Harbinson\n* Michael Klick\n* Claire Danes\n* [[Ron Nyswaner]]\n}}\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Lauren White\n* Katie O'Hara\n* Charlotte Stoudt\n* Mandy Patinkin\n}}\n| editor = {{Plainlist|\n* Joe Hobeck\n* Terry Kelley\n* Jordan Goldman\n* David Latham\n}}\n| location = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] {{small|(seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Tel Aviv, Israel]] {{small|(seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Old San Juan, Puerto Rico]] {{small|(season 3)}}\n* [[Morocco]], [[North Africa]] {{small|(seasons 3, 6, 8)}}\n* [[Cape Town, South Africa]] {{small|(season 4)}}\n* [[Berlin, Germany]] {{small|(season 5)}}\n* [[New York City, New York]] {{small|(season 6)}}\n* [[Richmond, Virginia]] {{small|(season 7)}}\n}}\n| cinematography = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Nelson Cragg]]\n* [[Dave Klein (cinematographer)|David Klein]]\n* Chris Manley\n}}\n| camera = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime = 46\u201384 minutes\n| company = {{Plainlist|\n* Teakwood Lane Productions\n* Cherry Pie Productions\n* [[Keshet Media Group|Keshet Broadcasting]]\n* Fox 21 (2011\u201314)\n* [[Fox 21 Television Studios]] (2015\u2013present)\n* [[Showtime Networks]]\n* [[Studio Babelsberg]]\n}}\n| distributor = [[20th Television]]\n| channel = [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n| picture_format = [[HDTV]] [[1080i]] \n| first_aired = {{Start date|2011|10|2}}\n| last_aired = present\n| website = http://www.sho.com/homeland\n}}\n\n'''''Homeland''''' is an American [[Spy fiction|spy thriller]] television series developed by [[Howard Gordon]] and [[Alex Gansa]] based on the Israeli series ''[[Prisoners of War (TV series)|Prisoners of War]]'' (Original title {{lang-he|\u05d7\u05d8\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05dd|translit=Hatufim}}, literally \"Abductees\"), which was created by [[Gideon Raff]].<ref name=\"Pickup\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news |url=http://tv.nytimes.com/show/5111863/Homeland/overview|title=Homeland \u2013 Listings|work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 30, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe series stars [[Claire Danes]] as [[Carrie Mathison]], a [[Central Intelligence Agency]] officer with [[bipolar disorder]], and [[Damian Lewis]] as [[Nicholas Brody]], a [[United States Marine Corps Scout Sniper|U.S. Marine Corps Scout Sniper]]. Mathison had come to believe that Brody, who was held captive by [[al-Qaeda]] as a [[prisoner of war]], was [[Defection|\"turned\"]] by the enemy and poses a threat to the United States. The series focuses on a storyline that evolves from this premise, together with Mathison's ongoing covert work.\n\nThe series is broadcast in the U.S. on the [[cable channel]] [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]], and is produced by [[Fox 21 Television Studios]] (formerly Fox 21). It premiered on October 2, 2011.<ref name=\"Premiere\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/07/21/showtime-releases-trailers-for-dexter-and-homeland-video-both-premiere-sunday-october-2/98635 |title=Showtime Releases Trailers for ''Dexter'' and ''Homeland'' (Video), Both Premiere Sunday, October 2 |date=July 21, 2011 |last=Seidman |first=Robert |work=[[TV by the Numbers]] |accessdate=August 20, 2011 }}</ref> The first episode was made available online more than two weeks before the television broadcast, with viewers having to complete game tasks to gain access.<ref name=\"WatchCareful\">{{cite web |title=Homeland |url=http://watchcareful.ly/ |publisher=[[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] |accessdate=September 15, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"THROnlinePilot\">{{cite news |title=Showtime Puts ''Homeland'' Pilot Online Ahead of October Premiere |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/showtime-puts-homeland-pilot-online-234692 |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 13, 2011 |first=Philiana |last=Ng }}</ref> The series' eighth and final season<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/08/11/homeland-renewed-season-8-showtime/ |title=''Homeland'' Officially Renewed for Season 7 and Season 8 at Showtime |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=August 11, 2016 |accessdate=August 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"FinalSeason\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/08/06/homeland-season-8-final/|title=Homeland will end with season 8, Showtime confirms|work=Entertainment Weekly|first=James|last=Hibberd|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018}}</ref> premiered on February 9, 2020.<ref name=\"Feb2020\">{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/08/02/homeland-final-season-8-premiere-date-showtime/|title=Homeland Final Season Pushed to 2020 \u2014 First Plot Details Revealed|work=TVLine|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|date=August 2, 2019|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe series has received generally positive reviews, with its first two seasons gaining near universal praise. It has won several awards, including the 2011 and 2012 [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama]] for its first two seasons, and the 2012 [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series]] for its first season. Danes has won the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]] twice (from five nominations) and Lewis has won the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] once (from two nominations). Supporting cast members [[Mandy Patinkin]], [[Morena Baccarin]], [[Rupert Friend]] and [[F. Murray Abraham]] have also received Emmy acting nominations.\n\n== Overview ==\n{{Main|List of Homeland episodes}}\n{{:List of Homeland episodes}}\n\n=== Season 1 (2011) ===\n{{Main|Homeland (season 1)}}\nCarrie Mathison, a [[Central Intelligence Agency]] [[agent handling#case officer|operations officer]], conducts an unauthorized operation in [[Iraq]] and is reassigned to the CIA's [[Counterterrorism Center]] in [[Langley, Virginia]]. Nicholas Brody, a [[U.S. Marine]] [[Sergeant#Marine Corps|Sergeant]] who had been reported as [[missing in action]] since 2003, is rescued from a compound belonging to terrorist Abu Nazir.  Brody is heralded as a war hero, but Carrie comes to suspect that he is planning a terrorist attack against the United States.\n\n=== Season 2 (2012) ===\n{{Main|Homeland (season 2)}}\nWhile on leave from the CIA, Carrie is recruited for an intelligence gathering mission in Beirut.Brody strengthens his position as a potential running mate for Vice President Walden, while still under the command of Abu Nazir...\n\n=== Season 3 (2013) ===\n{{Main|Homeland (season 3)}}\nIn the aftermath of the terrorist attack on Langley, Brody has fled the country while Carrie strives to clear his name.  An initiative by CIA director Saul Berenson targets Iranian intelligence officer Majid Javadi (who financed the Langley bombing).\n\n=== Season 4 (2014) ===\n{{Main|Homeland (season 4)}}\nCarrie is working as a CIA station chief in Kabul, Afghanistan and later in Islamabad, Pakistan.  She oversees a botched drone strike on the suspected location of terrorist mastermind Haissan Haqqani, which causes strife within the CIA and provokes the extremely dangerous terrorist.   Carrie recruits a young asset in an attempt to track down Haqqani. Information provided to the Pakistanis by a disgruntled embassy American leads to disastrous results.\n\n=== Season 5 (2015) ===\n{{Main|Homeland (season 5)}}\nTwo years after the events of season 4, Carrie is no longer an intelligence officer and is now working as head of security for a private charitable foundation and its billionaire owner in [[Berlin]], Germany.<ref name=S5>{{cite news |last1=Bibel |first1=Sara |title=''Homeland'' Season 5 and ''The Affair'' Season 2 to Premiere Sunday, October 4 on Showtime |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/07/23/homeland-season-5-the-affair-season-2-to-premiere-sunday-october-4-on-showtime/436133/ |accessdate=July 23, 2015 |work=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=July 23, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"berlin\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/04/27/homeland-going-germany-season-5 |title=''Homeland'' going to Germany for season 5 |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=April 27, 2015 |accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Season 6 (2017) ===\n{{main|Homeland (season 6)}}\nSeveral months after the previous season, Carrie is back in the United States, living in [[Brooklyn]], New York. She now works at a foundation that provides aid to Muslims living in the United States. The season features the election of the first female president and occurs between [[Election Day (United States)|election day]] and [[United States presidential inauguration|inauguration day]].<ref name=\"season6\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/homeland-renewed-seasons-season-6-debut-pushed-to-january-1201765619/ |title='Homeland' Nears Renewal For Seasons 7 & 8, Season 6 Debut Pushed To January |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=June 1, 2016 |accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Season 7 (2018) ===\n{{main|Homeland (season 7)}}\nCarrie has left her job in the White House and moved back to D.C. to live with her sister Maggie. She takes on the Keane administration to secure the release of the 200 members of the intelligence community who were arrested under President Keane's orders the previous season.<ref name=\"s7premiere\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/homeland-season-7-sets-premiere-date-trailer-showtime-1202637509/|title=\u2018Homeland\u2019 Season 7 Sets Premiere Date, Drops First Trailer|first=Joe|last=Otterson|work=Variety|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Season 8 (2020)===\n{{main|Homeland (season 8)}}\nSaul, now [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] to President Warner, is sent to Afghanistan to engage the Taliban in peace negotiations. He needs help from Carrie, who is recovering from her confinement in a Russian [[gulag]].<ref name=\"Feb2020\"/>\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{{main|List of Homeland characters}}\n[[File:Claire Danes.jpg|thumb|right|[[Claire Danes]] portrays series lead character [[Carrie Mathison]]]]\n* [[Claire Danes]] as [[Carrie Mathison]], a CIA case officer assigned to the [[Counterterrorism Center]]. She has [[bipolar disorder]] and believes Brody to be a terrorist when he returns to the United States. After leaving the CIA, Carrie becomes a private citizen, living in Berlin and later, New York.\n* [[Damian Lewis]] as [[Nicholas Brody]], a Congressman and retired [[U.S. Marine]] [[Gunnery Sergeant#Marine Corps|Gunnery Sergeant]] (formerly [[Sergeant]]) who is rescued by [[Delta Force]] after being held by [[al-Qaeda]] as a [[prisoner of war]] for eight years (starring seasons 1\u20133, guest season 4).\n* [[Mandy Patinkin]] as Saul Berenson, Carrie's mentor and the CIA's Middle East Division Chief and Acting Director of the CIA during season 3.\n* [[Morena Baccarin]] as Jessica Brody, Brody's wife. Assuming her husband is dead, she has a relationship with Mike. She struggles to adjust when Brody returns after such a long absence (seasons 1\u20133).\n* [[David Harewood]] as David Estes, the director of the CIA's Counter-terrorism Center and Carrie's boss. The two have a tumultuous relationship due to her aggressive way of working and the suggestion of a past sexual relationship between them (seasons 1\u20132).\n* [[Diego Klattenhoff]] as Mike Faber, a U.S. Marine [[Major (United States)#U.S. Army, U.S. Air Force, and U.S. Marine Corps|Major]] (formerly [[Captain (United States)#U.S. Army, U.S. Air Force, and U.S. Marine Corps|Captain]] in season 1). Brody's best friend who, assuming Brody is dead, begins a relationship with Jessica (starring seasons 1\u20132, guest season 3).\n* [[Jackson Pace]] as Chris Brody, Brody's son (seasons 1\u20133).\n* [[Morgan Saylor]] as Dana Brody, Brody's daughter (seasons 1\u20133).\n* [[Jamey Sheridan]] as William Walden, [[Vice President of the United States]] and a former director of the CIA (recurring season 1, starring season 2).\n* [[David Marciano]] as Virgil Piotrowski, a freelance surveillance expert and former CIA employee whom Carrie enlists for the surveillance of Brody (recurring seasons 1 and 3, starring season 2).\n* [[Navid Negahban]] as Abu Nazir, a high-ranking member of al-Qaeda (recurring season 1, starring season 2, guest season 3).\n* [[Rupert Friend]] as Peter Quinn, a CIA operative and assassin (recurring season 2, starring seasons 3\u20136).\n* [[Sarita Choudhury]] as Mira Berenson, Saul's wife (recurring seasons 1 and 4, guest seasons 2 and 6, starring season 3).\n* [[Tracy Letts]] as Senator Andrew Lockhart, who later assumes the role of Director of the CIA (seasons 3\u20134).\n* [[F. Murray Abraham]] as Dar Adal, a black ops specialist (recurring seasons 2 and 4, starring seasons 3 and 5\u20136, guest season 7).\n* [[Nazanin Boniadi]] as Fara Sherazi, a Muslim CIA analyst (recurring season 3, starring season 4).\n* [[Laila Robins]] as Martha Boyd, the United States ambassador to [[Pakistan]] (season 4).\n* [[Sebastian Koch]] as Otto D\u00fcring, a German philanthropist and Carrie's boss (starring season 5, guest season 6).\n* [[Miranda Otto]] as Alison Carr, the current Berlin Chief of Station, working directly for Saul Berenson (season 5).\n* [[Alexander Fehling]] as Jonas Hollander, legal counsel for the D\u00fcring Foundation and Carrie's boyfriend (season 5).\n* [[Sarah Sokolovic]] as Laura Sutton, an American journalist in [[Berlin]], who works for the D\u00fcring Foundation (season 5).\n* [[Elizabeth Marvel]] as Elizabeth Keane, a [[junior senator]] from New York, elected [[President of United States]] (seasons 6\u20137).\n* [[Maury Sterling]] as Max Piotrowski, Virgil's brother and a freelance surveillance expert who often works with Carrie (recurring seasons 1\u20134 and 6, starring seasons 7\u20138).\n* [[Linus Roache]] as David Wellington, [[White House Chief of Staff]] to President Keane (guest season 6, starring seasons 7\u20138).\n* [[Jake Weber]] as Brett O'Keefe, a [[right-wing]] media personality (recurring season 6, starring season 7).\n* [[Morgan Spector]] as Dante Allen, an old friend of Carrie's who is looking into the hundreds of people President Keane has detained (season 7).\n* [[Costa Ronin]] as [[Army ranks and insignia of the Russian Federation|Lieutenant Colonel]] Yevgeny Gromov, a Russian [[GRU]] Senior Operations Officer (recurring season 7, starring season 8).\n* [[Nimrat Kaur]] as [[Tasneem Qureishi]], a member of Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (recurring season 4, starring season 8).\n* [[Numan Acar]] as [[Haissam Haqqani]], a high-priority target and Taliban leader (recurring season 4, starring season 8).\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development history ===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Alex Gansa.jpg\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Howard_Gordon_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| width2 = 180\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = The series was developed for American television by [[Alex Gansa]] (''left'') and [[Howard Gordon]] (''right''). The two had previously worked together on ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'' and ''[[The X-Files]]''.\n}}\nBased on [[Gideon Raff]]'s Israeli series ''[[Hatufim]]'', ''Homeland'' was developed by [[Howard Gordon]] and [[Alex Gansa]] in early 2010. The two had previously worked together on the similarly themed series ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''.<ref name=\"Pickup\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/09/david-nevins-on-the-move-at-showtime-picks-up-thriller-from-howard-gordon|title=David Nevins On The Move At Showtime: Picks Up Thriller From Howard Gordon|date=September 19, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> On September 19, 2010, [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] placed a [[Television pilot|pilot]] order for ''Homeland'' as the first project [[David Nevins (television producer)|David Nevins]] had undertaken since leaving [[Imagine Entertainment]] to become president of Showtime.<ref name=\"Pickup\" /> Gordon, Gansa and Raff wrote the pilot, [[Michael Cuesta]] directed the pilot, with Gordon, Gansa, Raff, Avi Nir, and Ran Telem serving as executive producers.<ref name=\"Pickup\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/11/several-television-pilots-land-directors|title=Several Television Pilots Land Directors|date=November 12, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/11/claire-danes-eyes-showtime-series-lead|title=Claire Danes Eyes Showtime Pilot Lead|date=November 16, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe series was passed on by [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]<ref name=\"declassified\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/homeland-declassified-battles-backlash-cia-meetings-a-secret-call-edward-snowden-1269957 |title='Homeland' Declassified: Battles, Backlash, CIA Meetings and a Secret Call With Edward Snowden |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=January 16, 2020 |first=Michael |last=O'Connell |access-date=February 11, 2020}}</ref> before landing at Showtime who [[green-lit]] a 12 episode order on April 7, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/04/07/showtime-picks-up-house-of-lies-and-homeland-to-series/88643|title=Showtime Picks Up \"House of Lies\" and \"Homeland\" to Series|date=April 7, 2011|last=Seidman|first=Robert|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"fox 21\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/04/showtime-picks-up-homeland-house-of-lies-to-series|title=Showtime Picks Up 'Homeland' & 'House Of Lies' To Series|date=April 7, 2011|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showtime-greenlights-homeland-house-lies-176151|title=Showtime Greenlights 'Homeland,' 'House of Lies'|date=April 7, 2011|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 20, 2011|first=Philiana|last=Ng}}</ref> It was announced that [[Chip Johannessen]] would join the series as a co-executive producer, while Michael Cuesta, who had served as the director on the pilot, would join the series as an executive producer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dexter-showrunner-chip-johannessen-joins-181174|title=Former 'Dexter' Showrunner Chip Johannessen Joins Showtime's 'Homeland' (Exclusive)|date=April 21, 2011|last=Guthrie|first=Marissa|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/05/michael-cuesta-joins-showtime-series-homeland-as-executive-producer|title=Michael Cuesta Joins Showtime Series 'Homeland' As Executive Producer|date=May 4, 2011|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> [[Ben Affleck]] was originally slated to direct the pilot.<ref name=\"declassified\"/>\n\nOn July 21, 2011, at the [[San Diego Comic-Con International|San Diego Comic-Con]], Showtime announced that the series would premiere on October 2, 2011.<ref name=\"Premiere\" /> Along with the announcement of the premiere date for the series,<ref name=\"Premiere\" /> the network also announced that the names of the characters portrayed by Claire Danes and Damian Lewis had been renamed Carrie Mathison and Nicholas Brody, from Carrie Anderson and Scott Brody, respectively.<ref name=\"danes casting\"/><ref name=\"lewis casting\"/> The series is produced by [[Fox 21 (production company)|Fox 21]].<ref name=\"fox 21\"/>\n\nIn September 2016, Gansa announced that he would be crafting the eighth season as the series' last. He pointed out that the decision would ultimately fall on Showtime, but that he would be moving toward an eight-season close. He also stated that it would be his desire to film the final season in [[Israel]], where ''Homeland''{{'}}s source series, ''Prisoners of War'', originated.<ref name=\"TheFinalSeason\">{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/homeland-end-season-8-final-season-showruner-alex-gansa-showtime-1201821705/|title='Homeland': Showrunner Alex Gansa Eyes 8-Season Run For Showtime Series|date=September 18, 2016|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nCasting announcements began in November 2010, with [[Claire Danes]] first to be cast. Danes portrays Carrie Mathison, \"a driven CIA officer battling her own psychological demons.\"<ref name=\"danes casting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/11/its-official-claire-danes-to-star-in-showtimes-drama-pilot-homeland|title=It's Official: Claire Danes To Star In Showtime's Drama Pilot 'Homeland'|date=November 18, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/claire-danes-signs-star-showtimes-47140|title=Claire Danes to Star in Showtime's 'Homeland'|date=November 18, 2010|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 20, 2011|first=Philiana|last=Ng}}</ref> Other actresses considered for the Mathison role included [[Robin Wright]], [[Maria Bello]] and [[Halle Berry]].<ref name=\"declassified\"/> Next to join the series was [[Mandy Patinkin]] as Saul Berenson, \"the smart and politically savvy CIA Division Chief ... who is Carrie's main champion in the intelligence upper echelon and her sounding board.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/12/mandy-patinkin-in-showtimes-homeland|title=Mandy Patinkin In Showtime's 'Homeland'|date=December 9, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mandy-patinkin-signs-showtimes-homeland-60185|title=Mandy Patinkin Signs On for Showtime's 'Homeland'|date=December 15, 2010|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 20, 2011|first=Philiana|last=Ng}}</ref> [[Laura Fraser]] was initially cast as Jessica Brody, \"Nick Brody's smart, strong wife.\",<ref name=\"Fraser\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/12/tv-castings-laura-fraser-joins-showtime-pilot-homeland-two-added-to-true-blood|title=TV CASTINGS: Laura Fraser Joins Showtime Pilot 'Homeland,' Two Added To 'True Blood'|date=December 14, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> but after the pilot Fraser was replaced by [[Morena Baccarin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/05/v-star-morena-baccarin-joins-showtime-drama-series-homeland-as-regular|title='V' Star Morena Baccarin Joins Showtime Drama Series 'Homeland' As Regular|date=May 31, 2011|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> Next to join the series were [[Damian Lewis]] and [[David Harewood]], with Lewis playing Brody, \"who returns home after spending eight years as a prisoner of war in Baghdad\", while Harewood was cast as David Estes, \"a rising star in the CIA, Carrie's boss ... is the youngest director of the Counterterrorism Center in the Agency's history.\"<ref name=\"lewis casting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/12/damian-lewis-cast-as-the-male-lead-in-showtime-pilot-homeland|title=Damian Lewis Cast As The Male Lead In Showtime's Pilot 'Homeland'|date=December 21, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> Gansa pushed for Lewis in the Brody role despite hesitations from series producers in favor of [[Ryan Phillippe]], [[Kyle Chandler]] and [[Alessandro Nivola]].<ref name=\"declassified\"/> [[Diego Klattenhoff]], [[Morgan Saylor]], and [[Jackson Pace]] were the last actors to join the main cast, with Klattenhoff playing Mike Faber, \"Brody's close friend and fellow Marine, Mike Faber was convinced that Brody was dead, which is how he justified falling in love with Brody's wife Jessica\", Saylor playing Dana Brody, \"The Brodys' oldest child\", and Pace playing Chris Brody, \"Nick and Jessica's eager-to-please, self-conscious thirteen year-old son.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/01/pilot-castings-roundup-two-join-danni-lowinski-one-added-to-homeland|title=PILOT CASTINGS ROUNDUP: Two Join 'Danni Lowinski,' One Added To 'Homeland'|date=January 4, 2011|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/showtime-finalizes-cast-homeland-67535|title=EXCLUSIVE: Showtime Finalizes Cast for 'Homeland'|date=January 2, 2011|last=Guthrie|first=Marissa|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt was later announced that [[Jamey Sheridan]], [[Navid Negahban]], [[Amir Arison]], and [[Brianna Brown]] had joined the series as recurring guest stars. Sheridan was cast as the [[Vice President of the United States]], Negahban was cast as Abu Nazir, with Arison playing Prince Farid Bin Abbud and Brown playing Lynne Reed.<ref name=\"Negahban\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allyourtv.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2436:navid-negahban-cast-in-showtimes-homeland&catid=42:newspressreleases|title=Navid Negahban Cast In Showtime's 'Homeland'|work=All Your TV|accessdate=August 20, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928121932/http://www.allyourtv.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2436:navid-negahban-cast-in-showtimes-homeland&catid=42:newspressreleases|archivedate=September 28, 2011|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-showtime-series-adds-general-203874|title='Homeland': Showtime Series Adds 'General Hospital' Regular (Exclusive)|date=June 21, 2011|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nBeginning in season four, the showrunners began taking over the top floor of [[City Tavern Club]] in [[Washington D.C.]] for \"Spy Camp\". According to Gansa, the day would start at 8{{nbsp}}a.m. and end after 10{{nbsp}}p.m. where the writers, producers and some actors would meet with former CIA, ambassadors, ex-military, journalists and intelligence officers to discuss national security issues to inform the storylines. \"Spy Camp\" experts included [[A. Elizabeth Jones]], [[Stanley A. McChrystal]], [[Dana Priest]] and [[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]].<ref name=\"declassified\"/>\n\n''[[Washington Post]]'' writer [[Barton Gellman]] connected the ''Homeland'' team on an hours-long video call with [[Edward Snowden]] before he appeared in documentaries or did interviews. According to Patinkin, they could not \"budge him from his soapbox\" to discuss personal information while Snowden was in Moscow.<ref name=\"declassified\"/>\n\n=== Filming ===\nThe series is filmed in and around [[Charlotte]],  North Carolina. The location was chosen because of film [[tax credit]]s, and the atmosphere matches nearby [[Virginia]] and [[Washington, D.C.]], where the series is set.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlottemagazine.com/Charlotte-Magazine/October-2011/Showtimes-Homeland-filmed-in-Charlotte/|title=Showtime's Homeland filmed in Charlotte|work=Charlotte Magazine|first=Michelle|last=Boudin|date=October 2011|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Production claims it is easier to get around the area's smaller city atmosphere rather than in large cities where filming typically occurs.<ref name=Janes/> Another frequent setting is nearby [[Mooresville, North Carolina|Mooresville]]. Executive producer Michael Cuesta said Mooresville is \"played for quite a few rural-type one-stoplight main-street type of towns.\"<ref name=Janes/>\n\nThe Brody family house is in Mountainbrook, a Charlotte neighborhood near [[SouthPark Mall (Charlotte, North Carolina)|SouthPark Mall]]. [[Queens University of Charlotte]] is the Brody daughter's college. CIA headquarters is Cambridge Corporate Center in [[University City (Charlotte neighborhood)|University Research Park]]. [[Charlotte/Douglas International Airport]], the [[Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company#2000 and beyond|Ritz-Carlton]], the old courthouse, Ed's Tavern,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/eds-tavern-charlotte?select=qHZsjJxgs3rQFhvh0j7Orw#qHZsjJxgs3rQFhvh0j7Orw |title=From the Season 2 finale of Showtime's award winning Homeland series.  Shot right here at Ed's. |publisher=Yelp |date=March 15, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013}}</ref> and Zack's Hamburgers in Charlotte, as well as Rural Hill in [[Huntersville, North Carolina|Huntersville]] and [[Lake Norman]], have also served as filming locations.<ref name=\"Janes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/09/28/3563380/homeland-settling-into-charlotte.html#storylink=misearch|archive-date=January 19, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119051244/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/09/28/3563380/homeland-settling-into-charlotte.html%23storylink=misearch|url-status=dead|title='Homeland' settling into Charlotte, role as TV's top drama|last=Janes|first=Th\u00e9oden|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|date=September 30, 2012|accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nProduction for season two began in May 2012 with the series filming in [[Israel]] for two weeks, with Israeli cities standing in for Beirut.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newser.com/story/156081/homeland-filming-triggers-mideast-ruckus.html |title=''Homeland'' Filming Triggers Mideast Ruckus |publisher=Newser |first=Mary |last=Papenfuss |date=October 19, 2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/world/lebanon-angry-that-homeland-was-filmed-in-israel-1.37377 |title=Lebanon angry that Homeland was filmed in Israel |work=The JC |first=Jennifer |last=Lipman |date=October 19, 2012 |access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> The rest of the season was filmed in Charlotte and [[Concord, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite press|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2012/05/15/the-award-winning-showtime-series-homeland-welcomes-real-life-pow-hero-gilad-shalit-to-set-in-israel-755411/20120515showtime01|title=The Award-Winning Showtime(R) Series \"Homeland\" Welcomes Real-Life POW-Hero Gilad Shalit to Set in Israel|publisher=Showtime|date=May 15, 2012|accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nProduction for the third season began in late May 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/05/28/4068641/homeland-brings-claire-danes-to.html|title=Homeland shoots third season in uptown|first=Th\u00e9oden|last=Janes|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|date=May 28, 2013|accessdate=May 30, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215161307/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/05/28/4068641/homeland-brings-claire-danes-to.html|archive-date=December 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> continuing production in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Homeland' to film in Raleigh|url=http://www.wral.com/-homeland-to-film-in-raleigh/12493017/|work=[[WRAL-TV|WRAL]]|publisher=[[Capitol Broadcasting Company]]|date=May 29, 2013 |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> The series also filmed in [[Old San Juan, Puerto Rico]], which stood in for [[Caracas, Venezuela]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Puerto Rico Makes Debut on \"Homeland\"|url=http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/09/29/puerto-rico-makes-debut-on-homeland/|work=Caribbean Journal|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref> The series was also planning on returning to Israel for additional filming, but filming moved to Morocco, due to ongoing conflicts in [[Syrian Civil War|Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Homeland' Moves Israel Shoot to Morocco Amid Syria Debate|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-moves-israel-shoot-morocco-630796|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Michael|last=O'Connell|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProduction for the fourth season took place from June through November 2014 in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Showtime's 'Homeland' Set to Begin Production on Season 4|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/04/showtimes-homeland-set-to-begin-production-on-season-4/251227/|work=TV by the Numbers|first=Sara|last=Bibel|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> while the fifth season moved production to [[Berlin]], Germany.<ref name=\"berlin\"/>\n\nThe sixth season began production in August 2016 and filmed in New York City and Morocco.<ref name=\"season6\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/12/homeland-season-6 |title=''Homeland'' season 6 set in New York, Quinn won't be the same |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=January 12, 2016 |accessdate=January 12, 2016}}</ref> The seventh season began production on September 11, 2017, and primarily filmed in [[Richmond, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/homeland-virginia-season-7-film-showtime-1202491611/ |title=\u2018Homeland\u2019 Heads to Virginia for Season 7 |work=Variety |first=Cynthia |last=Littleton |date=July 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"DylanBaker\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/homeland-adds-dylan-baker-season-7-1044132 |title='Homeland' Adds Dylan Baker to Season 7 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Bryn Elise |last=Sandberg |date=September 28, 2017 |accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> Additional filming for season seven occurred in [[Budapest, Hungary]], for episodes 11 and 12.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.richmond.com/entertainment/television/showtime-s-homeland-premiered-sunday-find-out-which-parts-of/article_208d4964-3a7c-5f83-8dbf-8dcbe85df2ca.html |title=Showtime's 'Homeland' premiered Sunday. Find out which parts of Richmond you'll see this season |work=Richmond Times-Dispatch |first=Rob |last=Owen |date=February 10, 2018 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> The eighth season began filming in February 2019 in [[Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/01/07/homeland-season-8-morocco-setting-afghanistan-spoilers-carrie/|title=Homeland's End Game: Carrie Returning to [Spoiler] for Final Season|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|work=TVLine|date=January 7, 2019|accessdate=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other media===\nSince the conclusion of season 2, several pieces of in-universe material have been published.<ref name=\"other media\">{{cite web |url=http://www.slashfilm.com/homeland-announces-half-hour-audio-extra-narrated-by-damian-lewis/ |title='Homeland' Announces Half-Hour Audio Extra Narrated by Damian Lewis |publisher=/Film |first=Angie |last=Han |date=October 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> \n*HomelandAftermath.com provides a deeper look into the aftermath of season 2, with news reports and survivors' accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/redeye-homeland-trailer-web-site-explores-121212-attack-aftermath-tv-20130920-story.html |title='Homeland' trailer, Web site explores 12/12/12 attack aftermath |work=Chicago Tribune |first=Curt |last=Wagner |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n*Twentieth Century Fox partnered with [[Audible.com]] to offer ''Phantom Pain \u2013 A Homeland Story'' (2014), a 30-minute audio piece narrated by [[Damian Lewis]], which details Brody's movements between seasons 2 and 3 of the show.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://soundcloud.com/audibleuk/homeland-phantom-pain-narrated |title= 'Phantom Pain' A Homeland Story|authors=Gers, Glenn & Lewis, Damian (Narrator) |publisher=Audible UK |accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*''Homeland: Carrie's Run'' (2013) is a novel that tells the story of Carrie Mathison in a series of events that take place before season 1.<ref>{{cite web |author=Kaplan, Andrew|url=http://store.sho.com/homeland-carries-run-a-homeland-novel-paperback-book/detail.php?p=464961 |title=Homeland: Carrie's Run \u2013 A Homeland Novel (Paperback) Book |publisher=Showtime |accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*Another prequel novel set in 2009, ''Homeland: Saul's Game'' (2014), was released on October 7, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Homeland-Sauls-Game-Novel/dp/0062315455 |title=Homeland: Saul's Game: A Homeland Novel |author=Kaplan, Andrew|publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#284D68;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 1)|1]]\n| {{formatnum:100}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s01/|title=Homeland: Season 1 (2011)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:92}}<ref name=\"MetacriticS1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-1|title=Homeland: Season 1|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#0A0A0A;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 2)|2]]\n| {{formatnum:93}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s02/|title=Homeland: Season 2 (2012)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:96}}<ref name=\"MetacriticS2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-2|title=Homeland: Season 2|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#FFC50A;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 3)|3]]\n| {{formatnum:80}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s03/|title=Homeland: Season 3 (2013)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:77}}<ref name=\"MetacriticS3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-3|title=Homeland: Season 3|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#A91F24;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 4)|4]]\n| {{formatnum:81}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s04/|title=Homeland: Season 4 (2014)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:74}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-4|title=Homeland: Season 4|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#213035;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 5)|5]]\n| {{formatnum:88}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s05/|title=Homeland: Season 5 (2015)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:76}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-5|title=Homeland: Season 5|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#B6A4B1;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 6)|6]]\n| {{formatnum:78}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s06/|title=Homeland: Season 6 (2017)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:68}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-6|title=Homeland: Season 6|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#E7792A;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 7)|7]]\n| {{formatnum:80}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s07/|title=Homeland: Season 7 (2018)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=April 19, 2018}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:65}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-7|title=Homeland: Season 7|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=April 19, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#435692;\"|\n| [[Homeland (season 8)|8]]\n| {{formatnum:84}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/homeland/s08/|title=Homeland: Season 8 (2020)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{formatnum:71}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/homeland/season-8|title=Homeland: Season 8|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThe first season received near universal acclaim. [[Metacritic]] gave it a rating of 92 out of 100 based on 29 critics.<ref name=\"MetacriticS1\"/> ''[[TV Guide]]'' named it the best TV show of 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/special/best-of-year-2011/PhotoGallery/Best-Year-TV-1039885#1039886 |title=The Best TV Shows of 2011 |work=TV Guide |accessdate=December 12, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106230627/http://www.tvguide.com/special/best-of-year-2011/photogallery/Best-Year-TV-1039885 |archivedate=January 6, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and highly applauded the performances given by Damian Lewis and Claire Danes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/special/best-of-year-2011/PhotoGallery/Best-Performances-1039823#1040524|title=The Best Performances of 2011|work=TV Guide|accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref> Metacritic named ''Homeland'' the second-best TV show of 2011, based on aggregating the year-end top-ten lists of a number of major TV critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/tv-critic-top-10-best-shows-of-2011|title=2011 Television Critic Top Ten Lists|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> The second season also received near universal acclaim, achieving a Metacritic rating of 96 out of 100 from 21 critics.<ref name=\"MetacriticS2\"/> The third season initially received generally favorable reviews, with a rating of 77 out of 100 based on 23 critics,<ref name=\"MetacriticS3\"/> but reviews became more negative as the season progressed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan|first=Maureen|title='Homeland' Review: What The Heck Is Going On With This Show?|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/homeland-review_b_4125281.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=October 20, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=TV Critics Are Getting Fed Up With Homeland. Are You Still On Board?|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/homeland-season-3-reviews-game-on|publisher=Metacritic|first=Jason|last=Dietz|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Hank Stuever]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' gave the pilot episode an A\u2212, saying \"What makes ''Homeland'' rise above other post-9/11 dramas is Danes's stellar performance as Carrie\u2014easily this season's strongest female character,\" and that \"The latter half of the first episode is exhilarating. I'm hooked.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/artsandliving/television/features/2011/fall-tv|title=2011 TV season: Few smooth takeoffs, many bumpy arrivals|work=[[The Washington Post]]|first=Hank|last=Stuever|accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref> Matthew Gilbert of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' gave it a solid A grade, and said it was his favorite drama pilot of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-09-04/yourtown/30113340_1_bunnies-concept-rachel-bilson/7|title=Which new fall series make the grade?|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|first=Matthew|last=Gilbert|date=September 4, 2011|accessdate=September 27, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725111740/http://articles.boston.com/2011-09-04/yourtown/30113340_1_bunnies-concept-rachel-bilson/7|archivedate=July 25, 2012|df=}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s [[Ken Tucker]] gave it an A\u2212, stating \"It's the fall season's most intriguing, tense puzzler.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/tv/tonights_best_tv/0,,7,00.html|title=Homeland|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Ken|last=Tucker|accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref> [[IGN]] TV gave it a positive review, saying that it was an \"ace thriller\" that also managed to have something to say about the \"[[War on Terror]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/119/1197583p1.html|title=Homeland: \"Pilot\" Review|work=IGN|first=Scott|last=Collura|date=September 30, 2011|accessdate=October 2, 2011}}</ref> The seventh episode, \"[[The Weekend (Homeland)|The Weekend]]\", received overwhelming critical acclaim and was described by both the creators of the show and Lewis as a \"watershed\" episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sho.com/site/homeland/video.sho?bclid=1068235142001|title=With the Creators: The Weekend|publisher=Showtime|accessdate=December 16, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20111001063050/http://www.sho.com/site/homeland/video.sho?bclid=1068235142001|archivedate=October 1, 2011|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldderby.com/television/news/2220/damian-lewis-loves-keeping-viewers-'on-the-edge-of-their-seats'-in-'homeland'|title=Damian Lewis loves keeping viewers 'on the edge of their seats' in 'Homeland'|publisher=GoldDerby|first=Rob|last=Licuria|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Greg Dixon of ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' criticized ''Homeland''{{'}}s thin plotting, Danes's \"insane levels of overacting\", and Lewis's \"passivity\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/opinion/news/article.cfm?c_id=466&objectid=10839587 |title=Greg Dixon: Homeland nothing to write home about |work=The New Zealand Herald |first=Greg |last=Dixon |date=October 11, 2012 |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> Robert Rorke of ''[[New York Post]]'' wrote about the third season \"Seldom in the history of cable TV has a series imploded as quickly as Showtime's ''Homeland''.\" and \"The show, in the middle of its third season, is now impossible to take seriously.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2013/11/10/homeland-now-impossible-to-take-seriously/ |title='Homeland' impossible to take seriously |work=New York Post |first=Robert |last=Rorke |date=November 10, 2013 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Laura Durkay of ''The Washington Post'' criticized ''Homeland'' for its portrayal of Islamophobic stereotypes and called it \"the most bigoted show on television.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2014/10/02/homeland-is-the-most-bigoted-show-on-television/ |title=\u2018Homeland\u2019 is the most bigoted show on television |website=The Washington Post |first=Laura |last=Durkay |date=October 2, 2014 |access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFormer U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] has praised ''Homeland'' and is known to be a fan of the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/22/president-obama-homeland-damian-lewis_n_1373175.html |title=President Obama Will Give 'Homeland' A Foreign Policy Heads Up |date=March 22, 2012 |accessdate=September 24, 2012 |work=The Huffington Post |first=Chris |last=Harnick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Homelands-Damian-Lewis-1045142.aspx |title=Homeland's Damian Lewis Meets His No. 1 Fan: President Obama |work=TV Guide |first=Scott |last=Huver |date=March 22, 2012 |accessdate=September 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/emmys-2012-homeland-claire-danes-damian-lewis-barack-obama-373235 |title=Emmys 2012: 'Homeland' Stars on Their 'Hugely Validating' Fan, President Obama |work=The Hollywood Reporter |author1=O'Connell, Michael |author2=Nordyke, Kimberly |date=September 23, 2012 |accessdate=September 24, 2012}}</ref> Former Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]]'s office asked for early screeners of episodes from the first season.<ref name=\"declassified\"/>\n\n=== Ratings ===\nThe original broadcast of the pilot episode on October 2, 2011, received 1.08 million viewers, becoming Showtime's highest-rated drama premiere in eight years. The episode received a total of 2.78 million viewers with additional broadcasts and [[Video on demand|on demand]] views.<ref name=\"s1 premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/10/03/homeland-posts-best-new-drama-series-debut-ratings-on-showtime-in-8-years-dexter-sees-season-premiere-high/105852|title='Homeland' Posts Best New Drama Series Debut Ratings on Showtime in 8 Years; 'Dexter' Sees Season Premiere High|work=TV by the Numbers|first=Robert|last=Seidman|date=October 3, 2011|accessdate=October 3, 2011}}</ref> The final episode of season one received 1.7 million viewers, making it the most-watched season finale of any first-year Showtime series.<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118047717|title='Homeland' scores 1.7 million for Sunday finale|first=Stuart|last=Levine|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 19, 2011|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref>  Ratings increased in Season 2, peaking with 2.36 million viewers for the December 9, 2012 first-run broadcast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/12/dexter-homeland-hit-new-series-highs/|title='Dexter' & 'Homeland' Hit New Series Highs|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=December 11, 2012|accessdate=August 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe series has also performed well in the UK, where it airs on [[Channel 4]]. The pilot episode drew 2.2 million viewers and the season one finale drew 2.8 million viewers.<ref name=\"UK Ratings\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/oct/08/homeland-channel-4-tv-ratings |title=Homeland pulls in 2.3 million viewers |work=The Guardian |first=Mark |last=Sweney\t|date=October 5, 2012 |accessdate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> Season 2 saw a drop in viewership, with the season two premiere drawing in 2.3 million viewers,<ref name=\"UK Ratings\"/> but the finale only 2.1 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/dec/24/homeland-the-snowman-tv-ratings |title=Homeland beaten by The Snowman |work=The Guardian |first=Mark |last=Sweney |date=December 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Television season ratings\n| width         = 99\n| hide_rank     = y\n| hide_18_49_rating = y\n| hide_tv_season = y\n\n| link1            = Homeland (season 1)\n| timeslot1        = Saturday 10:00{{nbsp}}pm\n| timeslot_length1 = 2\n| episodes1        = 12\n| start1           = {{Start date|2011