umbers.zap2it.com/2014/12/23/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-wins-night-watch-what-happens-live-the-librarians-90-day-fiance-homeland-more/342347/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Real Housewives of Atlanta' Wins Night, 'Watch What Happens Live', 'The Librarians', '90 Day Fiance', 'Homeland' & More|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|accessdate=December 23, 2014|date=December 23, 2014}}</ref>\n| viewers4         = 1.65<ref name=\"S4ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/homeland-season-four-ratings-34377/|title=Homeland: Season Four Ratings|work=TV Series Finale|date=December 23, 2014|accessdate=October 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n| link5            = Homeland (season 5)\n| episodes5        = 12\n| start5           = {{Start date|2015|10|4}}\n| startrating5     = 1.66<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/homeland-the-affair-solid-season-debut-ratings-showtime-1201567323/ |title='Homeland' & 'The Affair' Ratings Solid In Season Starter Stats |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Lisa |last=de Moraes |date=October 5, 2015 |accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| end5             = {{End date|2015|12|20}}\n| endrating5       = 2.07<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/12/22/sunday-cable-ratings-dec-20-2015/|title=Sunday cable ratings: 'Homeland' rises with finale, 'Into the Badlands' hits season low|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=December 22, 2015|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref>\n| viewers5         = 1.53<ref name=\"S5ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/homeland-season-five-ratings-38474/|title=Homeland: Season Five Ratings|work=TV Series Finale|date=December 22, 2015|accessdate=October 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n| link6            = Homeland (season 6)\n| episodes6        = 12\n| start6           = {{Start date|2017|1|15}}\n| startrating6     = 1.08<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-jan-15-2017/|title=Sunday cable ratings: 'Young Pope' has so-so debut, 'Real Housewives of Atlanta' on top|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=January 18, 2017|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>\n| end6             = {{End date|2017|4|9}}\n| endrating6       = 1.90<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-april-9-2017/ |title=Sunday cable ratings: \u2018Homeland\u2019 ends with season high, \u2018Casey Anthony\u2019 strong for ID |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Rick |last=Porter |date=April 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n| viewers6         = 1.28<ref name=\"S6ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/homeland-season-six-ratings/|title=Homeland: Season Six Ratings|work=TV Series Finale|date=April 11, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n| link7            = Homeland (season 7)\n| episodes7        = 12\n| start7           = {{Start date|2018|2|11}}\n| startrating7     = 1.22<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-feb-11-2018/|title=Sunday cable ratings: \u2018Homeland\u2019 premiere steady, \u2018Real Housewives of Atlanta\u2019 improves|last=Porter|first=Rick|work=TV by the Numbers|date=February 13, 2018|accessdate=February 13, 2018}}</ref>\n| end7             = {{End date|2018|4|29}}\n| endrating7       = 1.30<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-april-29-2018/ |title=Sunday cable ratings: \u2018Westworld\u2019 and \u2018Fear the Walking Dead\u2019 dip |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Rick |last=Porter |date=May 1, 2018 |accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref>\n| viewers7         = 1.23<ref name=\"S7ratings\">{{cite web|url=https://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/homeland-season-seven-ratings/|title=Homeland: Season Seven Ratings|work=TV Series Finale|date=May 1, 2018|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n| link8            = Homeland (season 8)\n| episodes8        = 12\n| start8           = {{Start date|2020|2|9}}\n| startrating8     = 0.60<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-2-9-2020.html |title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 2.9.2020 |website=Showbuzz Daily |first=Mitch |last=Metcalf |date=February 11, 2020 |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| end8             = {{End date|2020|4|26}}\n| endrating8       = \n| viewers8         = \n}}\n\n=== Awards and nominations ===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Homeland}}\n\nIn its debut season, the series received several industry awards and nominations. The series was recognized with a [[Peabody Award]] in April 2012 describing the series as \"a game of cat and mouse, a psychological thriller and a Rorschach test of post-9/11 doubts, fears and suspicions rolled into one.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=COMPLETE LIST OF RECIPIENTS OF THE 71ST ANNUAL PEABODY AWARDS |url=http://www.peabody.uga.edu/71stwinners.php |publisher=The Peabody Awards |date=April 4, 2012 |accessdate=November 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601004713/http://www.peabody.uga.edu/71stwinners.php |archivedate=June 1, 2012 |df= }}</ref> At the [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards]], the series received nine nominations winning six awards, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]], [[Claire Danes]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]], [[Damian Lewis]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]], and [[Alex Gansa]], [[Howard Gordon]] and [[Gideon Raff]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series]] for the [[Pilot (Homeland)|pilot episode]]. The series also won awards for Outstanding Casting for a Drama Series and Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Drama Series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/homeland |title=Homeland |publisher=Emmys.com |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[69th Golden Globe Awards]], the series won the award for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Television Series \u2013 Drama]], and Claire Danes won for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama]], with Damian Lewis receiving a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]]. At the [[70th Golden Globe Awards]], the series won its second consecutive award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama, Danes won again for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama, and Lewis won for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama, after being nominated the previous year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/film/26364 |title=Homeland |publisher=GoldenGlobes.org |accessdate=October 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120529210937/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/film/26364 |archivedate=May 29, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nIn October 2012 the Lebanese government was reportedly planning to sue the show's producers, asserting misrepresentation of [[Hamra Street]] in [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]. Specifically, in the second episode of the second season \"[[Beirut Is Back]]\", the street was shown as a narrow alleyway with militia roaming and associated with terrorist activity. In reality, the Lebanese government says, it is a bustling modern hub of cafes and bars. The Minister of Tourism [[Fadi Abboud]] said he would take legal action over the lies, saying \"Beirut is one of the most secure capitals in the world, more secure than London or New York.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.executive-magazine.com/in-focus/homeland-beirut-lebanon-lawsuit-controversy/5269 |title=Whose Homeland is That? |work=Executive |last=Dyke |first=Joe |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=October 18, 2012}}</ref> Coincidentally, on October 19, 2012, [[Wissam al-Hassan]], a [[brigadier general]] of the Lebanese [[Internal Security Forces]] (ISF) and the head of its intelligence-oriented information branch, died along with several others killed by a [[car bomb]] in the [[Achrafieh]] district of [[Beirut]]. Although ''Homeland''{{'}}s co-creator, [[Gideon Raff]], is Israeli and thus forbidden from entering Lebanon, Abboud also protested the filming of episodes in Israel rather than Lebanon.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2012/oct/25/homeland-accurate-picture-middle-east-politics |title=Homeland: does it give an accurate picture of Middle East politics? |work=The Guardian |first=Ian |last=Black |date=October 25, 2012 |accessdate=November 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20002148 |title=Homeland angers minister over depiction of Beirut |publisher=BBC |date=October 19, 2012 |accessdate=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://fullcomment.nationalpost.com/2012/10/26/come-and-get-blown-up-in-sunny-beirut/ |title=Come and get blown up in sunny Beirut |work=National Post |first=Araminta |last=Wordsworth |date=October 26, 2012 |accessdate=November 20, 2012 |archive-url=http://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20130308004803/http://fullcomment.nationalpost.com/2012/10/26/come-and-get-blown-up-in-sunny-beirut/ |archive-date=March 8, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Beaumont (journalist)|Peter Beaumont]] of ''The Guardian'' wrote about the portrayal of Muslims in the series: \"High-profile Muslims living in the US share a secret: both willingly or otherwise they are covert helpers of Abu Nazir, the al-Qaida terrorist leader. In other words, it does not matter whether they are rich, smart, discreetly enjoying a western lifestyle or attractive: all are to be suspected.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/oct/13/homeland-drama-offensive-portrayal-islam-arabs |title=Homeland is brilliant drama. But does it present a crude image of Muslims? |work=The Guardian |first=Peter |last=Beaumont |date=October 13, 2012 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nRaff's works, ''Homeland'' included, have been criticized for their portrayal of Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/regajha/we-got-a-copy-of-the-script-for-alice-in-arabia-and-its-exac|title=We Got A Copy Of The Script For \"Alice In Arabia\" And It's Exactly What Critics Feared|date=March 21, 2014|publisher=[[Buzzfeed]]|first=Rega|last=Jha|accessdate=March 22, 2014}}</ref> In an article for ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', [[Laila Al-Arian]] called the show the most [[Islamophobic]] show on television, accused it of portraying Muslims under the light of simplistic concepts and as a monolithic, single-minded group whose only purpose is to hurt Americans, and basing the Brody character to such an extent on \"pseudo-psychology that only an audience conditioned by the Islamophobic, anti-Arab tropes in our media could find him consistent.\" She further criticizes the show for fanning hysteria of Muslim \"infiltration\" of the United States; poor mastery of even basic Arabic; misrepresentation of Islamic and Arab culture; and simplifying the politics of militant Islamic organizations, for instance by conflating groups that in real life are rivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/12/15/tvs_most_islamophobic_show/|title=Homeland, TV's Most Islamophobic Show|publisher=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=December 15, 2012|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAn article in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' by Yair Rosenberg challenged al-Arian's criticisms, arguing that they missed what made the show valuable, which was that it was no gung-ho salute to U.S. militarism and tactics on the war on terror nor a black-and-white portrayal of good Americans versus evil Muslims, but rather a show that challenges the prejudices of its viewers rather than affirming them.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Yair|title='Homeland' Is Anything but Islamophobic|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/12/homeland-is-anything-but-islamophobic/266418/|newspaper=The Atlantic|date=December 18, 2012|accessdate=March 22, 2014}}</ref> Similarly, Zach Novetsky asserted that al-Arian's criticisms was a function of the show's having enough \"depth and layers for someone to concoct a totally inaccurate interpretation of what the show really is about.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Novetsky|first=Zach|title='Homeland' Is Obviously Anti-Semitic|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/119607/homeland-is-obviously-anti-semitic|newspaper=Tablet Magazine|date=December 18, 2012|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMiddle East commentator [[Rachel Shabi]] wrote that ''Homeland'''s take on U.S. foreign policy in the Middle East does little more than defend the talking points of its advocates, presenting even U.S. violence against civilians as \"necessary acts in pursuit of far worse crimes\".<ref name=Guardian>{{cite web|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/oct/16/homeland-american-flag-waving|title=Does Homeland just wave the American flag?|date=October 16, 2012|accessdate=December 17, 2012|author2=Andreou, Alex|author1=Shabi, Rachel}}</ref>\n\nMiddle East policy expert [[Fawaz Gerges]] told [[TheWrap]], \"''Homeland'' is poisonous to any attempt to bridge the divide between the two nations [United States and Iran]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/does-showtime-homeland-create-tension-american-diplomacy/ |title=Iran Expert: Showtime's 'Homeland' Creates Tension for American Diplomacy |publisher=TheWrap |first=L.A |last=Ross |date=December 15, 2013 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe German news magazine ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' said that the show depicts \"hysterical CIA agents in a hysterical country,\" and demonstrates the \"paranoid tactics that delegitimize its democracy\" that the United States has applied and exceeded in real life, such as the tapping of German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]]'s phone.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/paranoia-has-undermined-united-states-claim-to-liberal-democracy-a-932326.html |title=Paradise Lost: Paranoia Has Undermined US Democracy |first=Dirk |last=Kurbjuweit |work=Der Spiegel |date=November 8, 2013 |accessdate=November 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 report, the [[human rights]] group [[Amnesty International]] found relatively high levels of popular support for torture in the U.S. and Britain, in part due to the glorification of torture allegedly found in popular English language TV shows such as ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'' and ''Homeland''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/05/13/more-britons-than-russians-support-torture_n_5313841.html|title=Homeland, Spooks And 24 Have Led More Britons Than Russians To Support Torture, Amnesty International Says|date=May 13, 2014|work=The Huffington Post UK|accessdate=May 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, three [[graffiti]] artists hired to add graffiti writings on the set of a season 5 episode (intended to portray a refugee camp on the [[Lebanon\u2013Syria border]]) to add \"authenticity\" to the scenes, wrote instead slogans accusing the show of racism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/oct/15/homeland-is-racist-artists-subversive-graffiti-tv-show|title='Homeland is racist': artists sneak subversive graffiti on to TV show |last=Phipps|first=Claire|date=October 15, 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Home video releases==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Episodes\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] release dates\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"