dia.org/wiki/Feira_de_Santana_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Amanda Kozak", "text_new": "{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name=Amanda Kozak Miliner\n| title=[[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]] 2006, [[Miss Georgia USA]] 2008\n| national competition=[[Miss America 2007]]  2nd runner-up), [[Miss USA 2008]]\n| birth_place= [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| birth_name= Amanda Kozak           \n| eye_color= Brown\n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1984|7|28}}\n| height={{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| hair_color=Brown\n}}\n\n'''Amanda Kozak-Miliner''' (born July 28, 1984) is a pageant titleholder and educator from [[Warner Robins, Georgia]] who competed in the [[Miss America]] and [[Miss USA]] pageants.<ref name=\"usa\" /> She is also the 2015 Georgia Teacher of the Year.<ref>Downey, Maureen. ''Fourth grade teacher Amanda Miliner of Houston County wins Georgia Teacher of the Year''. Atlanta Journal-Constitution, 2014, http://www.ajc.com/weblogs/get-schooled/2014/may/16/fourth-grade-teacher-amanda-miliner-houston-county/.</ref>\n\n==Pageants==\n\n===Miss America===\nKozak first competed in the [[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]] pageant in 2004 where she won a preliminary evening wear award made the top eleven.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Conyers Cherry Blossom wins second preliminary|date=2004-06-24|last=Associated Press|url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/georgia/news-article.aspx?storyid=20487|publisher=First Coast News}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The following year representing as Miss Warner Robins 2005 she placed first runner-up to Monica Pang. Kozak represented Georgia in the Miss National Sweetheart pageant, a competition for Miss America state runners-up, in September 2005, and placed first runner-up.<ref>{{cite news|title=Georgia\u2019s Kelley Bradshaw Wins National Sweetheart|publisher=The Chattanogan|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_92126.asp|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119025402/http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_92126.asp|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-01-19|date=2006-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, after winning the Miss Valdosta local title, Kozak competed in the Miss Georgia pageant. She won preliminary awards in both the evening gown and swimsuit competitions and was crowned [[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]] on 25 June.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Capital City Wins Second Preliminary|url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/georgia/news-article.aspx?storyid=59834|publisher=First Coast News|date=2006-06-21}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Valdosta wins Miss Georgia title|url=http://www.onlineathens.com/stories/062606/news_20060626021.shtml|date=2006-06-25|publisher=Athens Banner-Herald|last=Associated Press}}</ref>  Her platform for the state pageant was \"Positive Role Models Through Mentoring\".{{cn|date=September 2016}}\n\nKozak represented [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] in the [[Miss America]] 2007 pageant held in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] on 29 January 2007 and placed second runner-up to [[Lauren Nelson]] of [[Miss Oklahoma|Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Oklahoman Wins Miss America Crown|publisher=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/30/AR2007013000405.html?nav=rss_artsandliving/entertainmentnews|date=2007-01-30|first=Kathleen|last=Hennessey}}</ref> This was the second consecutive year that Georgia placed in the top three, as Pang had placed first runner-up at Miss America 2006. Kozak's talent was a [[tap dance]] performance, and her platform issue was Mentoring with the Big Brothers Big Sisters of America Organization. She was also a finalist for the Quality of Life award.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Miss America Quality of Life Finalists Announced|publisher=CMT News|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1550632/2007-miss-america-quality-of-life-finalists-announced.jhtml|date=2007-01-23}}</ref>\n\nKozak was given the key to the city of [[Valdosta, Georgia|Valdosta]] by mayor John Fretti and signs were erected in Valdosta congratulating her on her win.<ref name=\"home\">{{cite news|title=Miss Georgia returns home|date=2006-08-02|url=http://www.walb.com/Global/story.asp?S=5231393&nav=5kZQ|first=Alicia|last=Eaken|publisher=WALB 10 News|access-date=2010-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627175501/http://www.walb.com/Global/story.asp?S=5231393&nav=5kZQ|archive-date=2008-06-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Miss USA===\nOn November 10, 2007, she was crowned [[Miss Georgia USA]] 2008,  the first Georgian to win both state Miss America and Miss USA state titles.<ref name=\"usa\">{{cite news|title=Former Miss Valdosta is Miss Georgia again|publisher=The Valdosta Daily Times|url=http://valdostadailytimes.com/local/x1155891686/Former-Miss-Valdosta-is-Miss-Georgia-again|date=2007-11-15|first=Dean|last=Polling}}</ref><ref name=\"barron\">{{cite news|title=Former resident, beauty, competing for Miss USA title|publisher=Barron News Shield|url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=19469191&BRD=1132&PAG=461&dept_id=157660&rfi=6|date=2008-04-29|first=Eric|last=Quade|access-date=2010-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607230030/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=19469191&BRD=1132&PAG=461&dept_id=157660&rfi=6|archive-date=2011-06-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe represented Georgia at the [[Miss USA 2008]] pageant held on April 18 in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].  She did not place in the pageant, which was won by [[Crystle Stewart]] of [[Miss Texas USA|Texas]].\n\n==Georgia Teacher of the Year==\nOn May 16, 2014, Amanda Miliner (previously Kozak) was named the 2015 Georgia Teacher of the Year at the annual banquet ceremony. The Georgia Teacher of the Year serves as an advocate for public education in Georgia.{{cn|date=September 2016}}\n\n==Personal life==\nKozak's parents were both in the military, and she stayed with friends in Georgia while they were simultaneously deployed, including a one-year deployment in [[Korea]].<ref name=\"usa\" />  She is a graduate of [[Warner Robins High School]], has a bachelor's degree in Early Childhood Education from [[Valdosta State University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Supporters 'thrilled' about Miss Georgia's performance.|publisher=The Macon Telegraph |date=2007-01-31|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-158650606/supporters-thrilled-miss-georgia.html|first=Jenny|last=Gordon}}</ref> At the time she held the Miss Georgia title she was working as a third-grade teacher.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Georgia has message for Effingham students|date=2007-05-09|publisher=Savannah Morning News|url=http://savannahnow.com/node/281372|last=Curl|first=Eric}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://missgeorgiausa.com Miss Georgia USA official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081203141830/http://www.misswarnerrobins.org/history.php Miss Warner Robins official website]\n*[http://www.gadoe.org/External-Affairs-and-Policy/Excellence-Recognition/Pages/Georgia-Teacher-of-the-Year-Program.aspx Georgia Teacher of the Year program official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Brittany Swann]]\n| title=[[Miss Georgia USA]]\n| years=2008\n| after=Kimberly Gittings\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before=Monica Pang\n| title=[[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]]\n| years=2006\n| after=Leah Massee\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Miss USA 2008 delegates}}\n{{Miss America 2007 Delegates}}\n{{Georgia Pageant Winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kozak, Amanda}}\n[[Category:Miss America 2007 delegates]]\n[[Category:Miss USA 2008 delegates]]\n[[Category:Valdosta State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:People from Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name=Amanda Kozak Miliner\n| title=[[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]] 2006, [[Miss Georgia USA]] 2008\n| national competition=[[Miss America 2007]]  2nd runner-up), [[Miss USA 2008]]\n| birth_place= [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| birth_name= Amanda Kozak           \n| eye_color= Brown\n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1984|7|28}}\n| height={{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| hair_color=Brown\n}}\n\n'''Amanda Kozak-Miliner''' (born July 28, 1984) is a pageant titleholder and educator from [[Warner Robins, Georgia]] who competed in the [[Miss America]] and [[Miss USA]] pageants.<ref name=\"usa\" /> She is also the 2015 Georgia Teacher of the Year.<ref>Downey, Maureen. ''Fourth grade teacher Amanda Miliner of Houston County wins Georgia Teacher of the Year''. Atlanta Journal-Constitution, 2014, http://www.ajc.com/weblogs/get-schooled/2014/may/16/fourth-grade-teacher-amanda-miliner-houston-county/.</ref>\n\n==Pageants==\n\n===Miss America===\nKozak first competed in the [[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]] pageant in 2004 where she won a preliminary evening wear award made the top eleven.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Conyers Cherry Blossom wins second preliminary|date=2004-06-24|last=Associated Press|url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/georgia/news-article.aspx?storyid=20487|publisher=First Coast News}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  The following year representing as Miss Warner Robins 2005 she placed first runner-up to Monica Pang. Kozak represented Georgia in the Miss National Sweetheart pageant, a competition for Miss America state runners-up, in September 2005, and placed first runner-up.<ref>{{cite news|title=Georgia\u2019s Kelley Bradshaw Wins National Sweetheart|publisher=The Chattanogan|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_92126.asp|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119025402/http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_92126.asp|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-01-19|date=2006-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, after winning the Miss Valdosta local title, Kozak competed in the Miss Georgia pageant.  She won preliminary awards in both the evening gown and swimsuit competitions and was crowned [[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]] on 25 June.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Capital City Wins Second Preliminary|url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/georgia/news-article.aspx?storyid=59834|publisher=First Coast News|date=2006-06-21}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Valdosta wins Miss Georgia title|url=http://www.onlineathens.com/stories/062606/news_20060626021.shtml|date=2006-06-25|publisher=Athens Banner-Herald|last=Associated Press}}</ref>  Her platform for the state pageant was \"Positive Role Models Through Mentoring\".{{cn|date=September 2016}}\n\nKozak represented [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] in the [[Miss America]] 2007 pageant held in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] on 29 January 2007 and placed second runner-up to [[Lauren Nelson]] of [[Miss Oklahoma|Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Oklahoman Wins Miss America Crown|publisher=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/30/AR2007013000405.html?nav=rss_artsandliving/entertainmentnews|date=2007-01-30|first=Kathleen|last=Hennessey}}</ref>  This was the second consecutive year that Georgia placed in the top three, as Pang had placed first runner-up at Miss America 2006.  Kozak's talent was a tap dance performance, and her platform issue was Mentoring with the Big Brothers Big Sisters of America Organization.  She was also a finalist for the Quality of Life award.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Miss America Quality of Life Finalists Announced|publisher=CMT News|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1550632/2007-miss-america-quality-of-life-finalists-announced.jhtml|date=2007-01-23}}</ref>\n\nKozak was given the key to the city of [[Valdosta, Georgia|Valdosta]] by mayor John Fretti and signs were erected in Valdosta congratulating her on her win.<ref name=\"home\">{{cite news|title=Miss Georgia returns home|date=2006-08-02|url=http://www.walb.com/Global/story.asp?S=5231393&nav=5kZQ|first=Alicia|last=Eaken|publisher=WALB 10 News|access-date=2010-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627175501/http://www.walb.com/Global/story.asp?S=5231393&nav=5kZQ|archive-date=2008-06-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Miss USA===\nOn November 10, 2007, she was crowned [[Miss Georgia USA]] 2008,  the first Georgian to win both state Miss America and Miss USA state titles.<ref name=\"usa\">{{cite news|title=Former Miss Valdosta is Miss Georgia again|publisher=The Valdosta Daily Times|url=http://valdostadailytimes.com/local/x1155891686/Former-Miss-Valdosta-is-Miss-Georgia-again|date=2007-11-15|first=Dean|last=Polling}}</ref><ref name=\"barron\">{{cite news|title=Former resident, beauty, competing for Miss USA title|publisher=Barron News Shield|url=http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=19469191&BRD=1132&PAG=461&dept_id=157660&rfi=6|date=2008-04-29|first=Eric|last=Quade|access-date=2010-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607230030/http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=19469191&BRD=1132&PAG=461&dept_id=157660&rfi=6|archive-date=2011-06-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nShe represented Georgia at the [[Miss USA 2008]] pageant held on April 18 in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].  She did not place in the pageant, which was won by [[Crystle Stewart]] of [[Miss Texas USA|Texas]].\n\n==Georgia Teacher of the Year==\nOn May 16, 2014, Amanda Miliner (previously Kozak) was named the 2015 Georgia Teacher of the Year at the annual banquet ceremony. The Georgia Teacher of the Year serves as an advocate for public education in Georgia.{{cn|date=September 2016}}\n\n==Personal life==\nKozak's parents were both in the military, and she stayed with friends in Georgia while they were simultaneously deployed, including a one-year deployment in [[Korea]].<ref name=\"usa\" />  She is a graduate of [[Warner Robins High School]], has a bachelor's degree in Early Childhood Education from [[Valdosta State University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Supporters 'thrilled' about Miss Georgia's performance.|publisher=The Macon Telegraph |date=2007-01-31|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-158650606/supporters-thrilled-miss-georgia.html|first=Jenny|last=Gordon}}</ref> At the time she held the Miss Georgia title she was working as a third-grade teacher.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Georgia has message for Effingham students|date=2007-05-09|publisher=Savannah Morning News|url=http://savannahnow.com/node/281372|last=Curl|first=Eric}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://missgeorgiausa.com Miss Georgia USA official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081203141830/http://www.misswarnerrobins.org/history.php Miss Warner Robins official website]\n*[http://www.gadoe.org/External-Affairs-and-Policy/Excellence-Recognition/Pages/Georgia-Teacher-of-the-Year-Program.aspx Georgia Teacher of the Year program official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Brittany Swann]]\n| title=[[Miss Georgia USA]]\n| years=2008\n| after=Kimberly Gittings\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before=Monica Pang\n| title=[[Miss Georgia (U.S. state)|Miss Georgia]]\n| years=2006\n| after=Leah Massee\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Miss USA 2008 delegates}}\n{{Miss America 2007 Delegates}}\n{{Georgia Pageant Winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kozak, Amanda}}\n[[Category:Miss America 2007 delegates]]\n[[Category:Miss USA 2008 delegates]]\n[[Category:Valdosta State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:People from Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n", "name_user": "TMProofreader", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMiss America", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanda_Kozak"}
